        <h2 style="margin-top: var(--space-xl);">Estate Planning & Probate</h2>

        <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>How do I avoid probate in Pennsylvania?</h3>
            <p>Several strategies can help minimize or avoid probate. Holding assets in joint tenancy with right of survivorship allows them to pass automatically to the surviving owner. Naming beneficiaries on retirement accounts and life insurance keeps those assets out of probate entirely. Payable-on-death (POD) and transfer-on-death (TOD) designations on bank and investment accounts work similarly. A revocable living trust can hold other assets outside probate. The right combination depends on your assets, family situation, and goals — which is why we tailor every plan to the individual client rather than offering a one-size-fits-all approach.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>What happens if you die without a will in Pennsylvania?</h3>
            <p>Pennsylvania's intestacy statute (20 Pa.C.S. Chapter 21) determines who inherits when there is no valid will. If you are married with no children, your spouse inherits everything. If you have a surviving spouse and children who are also your spouse's children, your spouse receives the first $30,000 plus half of the remaining balance, and the children share the rest equally. Without a spouse, children inherit in equal shares. Without a spouse or children, parents inherit. Without parents, siblings inherit. These default rules rarely match what most people would choose — which is why having a will is so important.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>How much does Pennsylvania inheritance tax cost?</h3>
            <p>Pennsylvania imposes an inheritance tax based on the relationship between the deceased person and the beneficiary. The rates are: 0% for transfers to a surviving spouse, 4.5% for transfers to lineal descendants (children, grandchildren) and lineal ancestors (parents), 12% for transfers to siblings, and 15% for transfers to all other beneficiaries including nieces, nephews, friends, and unmarried partners. Life insurance proceeds paid to a named beneficiary are exempt from Pennsylvania inheritance tax. There are also exemptions for certain farmland and family-owned businesses. Our <a href="/resources/">free PA Inheritance Tax Guide</a> covers this in detail.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>What is a power of attorney and do I need one?</h3>
            <p>A power of attorney is a legal document that authorizes someone you trust (your "agent") to act on your behalf. A financial power of attorney covers decisions about your money, property, and financial affairs. A healthcare power of attorney (or healthcare directive) covers medical decisions if you cannot make them yourself. Every adult over 18 should have both documents in place. Without them, your family may need to petition the court for guardianship if you become incapacitated — a process that is expensive, time-consuming, and public. A properly drafted power of attorney avoids that entirely.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>How do I transfer a house after someone dies in Pennsylvania?</h3>
            <p>The process depends on how the property was titled. If the property was held in joint tenancy with right of survivorship, it passes automatically to the surviving owner — you will need a death certificate and typically an affidavit of survivorship recorded with the county recorder of deeds. If the property was held solely by the deceased, it must pass through probate. The executor or administrator transfers the property by executor's deed after the estate is opened with the Register of Wills. If the property was held in a revocable living trust, the successor trustee handles the transfer by trustee's deed without going through probate.</p>
        </div>

