            <h3>Do I need a lawyer for a real estate closing in PA?</h3>
            <p>Pennsylvania does not legally require an attorney at closing, but having one provides significant protection. An attorney reviews the agreement of sale for issues, conducts or reviews the title search for liens and encumbrances, explains the legal implications of every document you sign, identifies potential problems before you get to the settlement table, and ensures the transaction is recorded properly with the county. For most people, buying or selling a home is the largest financial transaction of their life — attorney representation is a wise investment.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>What is the difference between an LLC and a corporation in Pennsylvania?</h3>
            <p>Both LLCs and corporations provide personal liability protection, but they differ in structure, taxation, and formality requirements. An LLC offers flexible management (member-managed or manager-managed), pass-through taxation by default, and fewer ongoing formality requirements. A corporation has a more rigid governance structure with officers, directors, and shareholders, and may be subject to double taxation at the corporate and individual level — unless it elects S-corporation status. LLCs are generally better suited for small businesses and real estate holdings, while corporations may be advantageous for businesses seeking outside investment or planning to go public. We help clients choose the right structure based on their specific goals and tax situation.</p>
        </div>

